    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix UL 64QAM capability checking in RRC eNB\n\n### Summary\nThe `is_ul_64QAM_supported` function in `rrc_eNB.c` was causing segmentation faults when processing UE capability information from certain UEs. The function attempted to access deeply nested ASN.1 structures without proper null checking, leading to crashes during RRC connection setup.\n\nThe issue occurred when UEs did not include the full chain of non-critical extensions expected by the current implementation. In particular, when `supportedBandListEUTRA_v1250` was present but empty, or when intermediate extension levels were missing, the function would attempt to dereference null pointers.\n\nThis fix updates all QAM capability checking functions (`is_ul_64QAM_supported`, `is_dl_256QAM_supported`, and `is_ul_256QAM_supported`) to:\n1. Use the standard `NCE` macro for accessing nested structures consistently\n2. Add proper array bounds checking using `list.count` before accessing array elements\n3. Add null pointer checks for all intermediate structure accesses\n\n### Reproduction\nThe issue can be reproduced by connecting a UE that reports EUTRA capabilities without including all optional v1250 or v1430 extensions. During the RRC connection reconfiguration phase, the eNB will call these functions to check UE capabilities, resulting in a segmentation fault.\n\nSymptoms include:\n- gNB process termination with SIGSEGV\n- RRC connection setup failures\n- UE unable to establish data connection\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/RRC/LTE/rrc_eNB.c`: Updated `is_ul_64QAM_supported`, `is_dl_256QAM_supported`, and `is_ul_256QAM_supported` functions to use proper null checking and array bounds validation\n"
}